9":"1388–1429","about 1380":"omkring 1380","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1413":"1413","1422":"1422","1388":"1388","1452":"1452","1485":"1485","from 1422 to 1439":"fra 1422 til 1439","1429":"1429","1439":"1439","1505":"1505","1427":"1427","Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Irland","Donegal, County Tipperary, Ireland":"Donegal, County Tipperary, Irland","Isle of Man":"Isle of Man","Tirconnell, County Donegal, Ireland":"Tirconnell, County Fermanagh, Irland","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Irland"},"nl":{"about 1380–1439":"circa 1380–1439","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1392–1439":"1392–1439","1427–1505":"1427–1505","1393–1485":"1393–1485","1413–1452":"1413–1452","1350–1422":"1350–1422","1388–1429":"1388–1429","about 1380":"circa 1380","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1413":"1413","1422":"1422","1388":"1388","1452":"1452","1485":"1485","from 1422 to 1439":"van 1422 to 1439","1429":"1429","1439":"1439","1505":"1505","1427":"1427","Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Ierland","Donegal, County Tipperary, Ireland":"Donegal, County Tipperary, Ierland","Isle of Man":"Man","Tirconnell, County Donegal, Ireland":"Tirconnell, County Fermanagh, Ierland","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ierland"},"en":{"about 1380–1439":"about 1380–1439","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1392–1439":"1392–1439","1427–1505":"1427–1505","1393–1485":"1393–1485","1413–1452":"1413–1452","1350–1422":"1350–1422","1388–1429":"1388–1429","about 1380":"about 1380","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1413":"1413","1422":"1422","1388":"1388","1452":"1452","1485":"1485","from 1422 to 1439":"from 1422 to 1439","1429":"1429","1439":"1439","1505":"1505","1427":"1427","Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Ireland","Donegal, County Tipperary, Ireland":"Donegal, County Tipperary, Ireland","Isle of Man":"Isle of Man","Tirconnell, County Donegal, Ireland":"Tirconnell, County Fermanagh, Ireland","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"O'Donnell,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brigid, Niall, Siobhan, Brennan, Bridie, Declan, Donal, Fergus, Jarlath, John Patrick, Padraic.","Irish (Donegal, Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Domhnaill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Domhnall</i>’, an old personal name composed of the Celtic elements <i>domno-</i> ‘world’ + <i>val-</i> ‘might, rule’. Compare the Anglicized form   Donald   and the Scottish clan name   McDonald  .","History: The O'Donnells, like the O'Neills (see   O'Neill  ), claim descent from Niall of the Nine Hostages (Niall Noígíallach), a legendary 5th-century king of Ireland. Their traditional base is Tyrconnell (i.e. Donegal)."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Donell","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Donnel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Daniel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  , influenced by the Biblical name   Daniel  , to which it is etymologically unrelated."]},{"name":"O'Donald","meanings":["Irish: Scotticized form of   O'Donnell  . The Irish personal name <i>Domhnall</i> was Latinized as <i>Donaldus</i>, which is the source of <i>Donald</i>, the form of the personal name used in English in Scotland, though not in Ireland. The form <i>O'Donald</i> is therefore a 19th-century hybrid. Compare   Donald  ."]},{"name":"Donald","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McDonald   (<i>Mac Dhomhnaill</i>), from the Gaelic personal name <i>Domhnall</i>; found in 13th- and 14th-century Scotland as <i>Dofnald</i>, <i>Douenald</i>, <i>Dufenald</i>, and <i>Donald</i>.","Irish (Ulster): possibly also a shortened and altered form of Irish   O'Donell  ."]}]},{"name":"Niall","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of disputed derivation; it may mean ‘cloud’, ‘passionate’, or perhaps ‘champion’. It was adopted by the Scandinavians in the form <i>Njal</i> and soon became very popular among them. From the Middle Ages onwards, this name was found mainly in Ireland, the Highlands of Scotland, and the English-Scottish Border region. However, it has been strongly revived among non-Gaelic speakers since the latter part of the 20th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Neal","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Neil ."]},{"name":"Neale","meanings":["Anglicized form of the enduringly popular Gaelic name   Niall .  From the Middle Ages onwards, this name was found mainly in Ireland, the Highlands of Scotland, and the English-Scottish Border region. However, since the 20th century it has spread to enjoy considerable popularity in all parts of the English-speaking world, although in England it has recently been overtaken by the Gaelic form."]},{"name":"Neil","meanings":["Anglicized form of the enduringly popular Gaelic name   Niall .  From the Middle Ages onwards, this name was found mainly in Ireland, the Highlands of Scotland, and the English-Scottish Border region. However, since the 20th century it has spread to enjoy considerable popularity in all parts of the English-speaking world, although in England it has recently been overtaken by the Gaelic form."]}]},{"name":"Garbh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of a surname, but often taken to be a contracted form of   Gareth .  As a surname it originated in the north of England, as a local name for someone who lived near an enclosure of some sort (Old Norse <i>garðr</i>). In modern times its popularity has been influenced by the virile superhero of this name, the main character in a long-running strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror newspaper."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354212,"age":15,"year":"1395","julianDay":2230574,"description":"Le Scrope, King of 